<DOC><DOCNO> AP880219-0047 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-19-88 0503EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     02-19 0435</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,420</SECOND><HEAD>FTC Grilled on Department Store Merger</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Federal Trade Commission has been asked toinvestigate its staff's review of a proposed takeover of FederatedDepartment Stores Inc. and report back to a congressional panelnext week.   Testimony by the FTC before the House Energy and Commercetransportation subcommittee on Thursday was cut short after thecommissioners said they were not familiar with the details of thereview.   Subcommittee chairman Rep. Thomas Luken, D-Ohio, dismissed thecommissioners after several unsuccessful attempts to question themon why the agency decided not to pursue a further, more extensiveinvestigation into potential anticompetitive effects of the mergerbetween the Cincinnati-based Federated and Campeau Corp. of Canada.   FTC Chairman Daniel Oliver said the agency's bureau ofcompetition spent 250 hours reviewing the merger and ``I haveconfidence in the bureau director.''</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Contra Aid Foes To Be Arraigned For Unlawful Entry On Capitol Hill</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Two Baltimore men who oppose U.S. aid to theNicaraguan Contra rebels were to be arraigned today on charges ofunlawful entry after they refused to leave the Capitol Hill officeof Rep. Lee Hamilton, authorities said.   Michael Bardoff, 30, and Kevin Hornbuckle, 25, were arrested at7 p.m. Thursday and charged with unlawful entry at the IndianaDemocrat's office, said U.S. Capitol Police Officer Dan Nichols.   Bardoff was detained overnight in the District of Columbia jailafter a bond hearing, while Hornbuckle was released on his ownrecognizance, Nichols said. Both were scheduled for arraignmenttoday in Superior Court.   The two had entered Hamilton's office at 2:30 p.m. and had vowedto remain there ``until they received assurances that Contra aidwould not go through the CIA,'' said Richard Ochs, a spokesman forthe Baltimore Emergency Response Network, a group that opposesContra aid.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Spielberg Speaks Out Against Movie Colorization</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A Senate sucommittee plans to hear fromfilmmakers Steven Spielberg and George Lucas next month as itconsiders expanding the nation's copyright laws to prevent thecontroversial coloring of black-and-white films.   The Directors Guild of America said Thursday that Spielberg andLucas, who between them have made some of the world's biggestmoneymaking movies, will testify March 3 before the SenateJudiciary subcommittee on patents, copyrights and trademarks infavor of legislation giving directors the ``moral rights'' overchanges in their completed works.   Spielberg, who opposes the coloring of old films, said in astatement Thursday: ``Moral rights are essential to protect futuregenerations from the kind of big business greed that doesn't careabout the desecration of timeless treasures.''</TEXT></DOC>